[[ファイル:Kawaketamikabe-jinja, torii.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Torii}}]]
'''Kawaketamikabe Shrine''' (かわけたみかべじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{読み仮名|Jinden-chō|じんでんちょう}}, {{ill|lt=Higashiōmi|Q240891|qid=Q240891|1=Higashiōmi}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|qid=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}. It is a candidate for a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. The shrine crest is Dakisawagata.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ame-no-Yukaketa-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Seoritsu-hime-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}
* Inakura-tama-no-Mikoto

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, it was solicited in year 4 of {{ill|lt=Emperor Senka|Q329728|qid=Q329728|1=Emperor Senka}} by local powerful clan leader Tamao Sukune Isotohiko no Muraji. It is a candidate shrine for the Engishiki {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} "Kawaketa Shrine." In ancient times it was called "Mikawabe Daimyōjin." The present shrine building is said to have been rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|qid=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 15 ({{ill|lt=1610|Q6765|qid=Q6765|1=1610}}) by Tanaka Yoshihisa, and a ridge tag records "Kaki Misono Mikawabe Shōichii Daimyōjin, Kanzaki District, Gōshū." In early {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}, it was renamed to the current shrine name, and in Meiji 14 ({{ill|lt=1881|Q7808|qid=Q7808|1=1881}}) was added as {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

[[ファイル:Kanekai Site, gaikan.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Kanekai archaeological site}}]]
In {{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|qid=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 20 ({{ill|lt=2008|Q2004|qid=Q2004|1=2008}}), posthole remains believed to be an early Heian three-bay {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|qid=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}} honden were found at the nearby Kanekai site<ref>Shiga Prefecture cultural properties, historic sites (2012)</ref>, and one theory infers a relationship with this shrine.

